{
  "result": "At the edge of my town there is a train platform nobody uses after sunset, and I like it that way. In daylight it is practical and noisy: commuters checking watches, students balancing coffee cups, announcements flattening every conversation into static. But at night it becomes a stage built for weather. Wind rehearses along the tracks, rain taps the metal roof in patient code, and the yellow lamps hum like old violins warming up.\n\nI go there when my thoughts are too loud to sort. Something about the rails helps; they are honest lines, admitting exactly where they have been and where they are willing to go. No pretending, no mystery, just direction. Sitting on the cold bench, I imagine every train as a different version of my life arriving right on schedule. One carries the life where I moved to the coast. Another, the one where I learned piano at ten and never stopped. Another, improbably, where I became brave much earlier.\n\nNone of them are mine now, and that used to feel like loss. Lately it feels more like proof that possibility is still circulating, even if it does not stop for me tonight. I can wait. I can listen. Somewhere beyond the curve, steel begins to sing before the engine appears, and for a few seconds everything\u2014past, present, fear, desire\u2014fits inside a single, shining note. Then the sound fades, the platform exhales, and I walk home lighter, carrying nothing visible except the small courage of staying open.",
